      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "smolagents: CodeAgent"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "smolagents' flagship agent is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CodeAgent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Instead of emitting a JSON tool-call specification, the LLM writes a Python snippet that calls the registered tools. The snippet is executed in a sandboxed environment. The agent can chain tool calls, compute intermediate values, and use loops \u2014 any valid Python that uses the defined tools."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from smolagents import CodeAgent, tool, LiteLLMModel\nfrom typing import Optional\n\n# Define tools with @tool and a docstring\n@tool\ndef calculate(expression: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Evaluate a safe arithmetic expression and return the result as a string.\n    Args:\n        expression: A Python arithmetic expression, e.g. '2 ** 10' or '3.14 * 5'.\n    \"\"\"\n    import math\n    allowed = {k: v for k, v in math.__dict__.items() if not k.startswith(\"_\")}\n    allowed.update({\"abs\": abs, \"round\": round})\n    try:\n        return str(eval(expression, {\"__builtins__\": {}}, allowed))\n    except Exception as e:\n        return f\"Error: {e}\"\n\n@tool\ndef get_word_count(text: str) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    Count the number of words in a text string.\n    Args:\n        text: The text to count words in.\n    \"\"\"\n    return len(text.split())\n\n# Use any LLM via LiteLLM\nmodel = LiteLLMModel(model_id=\"gpt-4o\")\n\n# CodeAgent: LLM generates Python code that calls tools\nagent = CodeAgent(\n    tools=[calculate, get_word_count],\n    model=model,\n    max_steps=5,\n)\n\nresult = agent.run(\n    \"What is 2 to the power of 20?\"\n    \" Also tell me how many words are in 'the quick brown fox jumps'.\"\n)\nprint(result)\n# The LLM writes:\n#   power_result = calculate(\"2 ** 20\")\n#   word_result = get_word_count(\"the quick brown fox jumps\")\n#   final_answer(f\"2^20 = {power_result}. Word count: {word_result}.\")\n# Output: 2^20 = 1048576. Word count: 5."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@tool",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " decorator uses the function's docstring to describe each argument to the LLM. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Args:",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " section lists parameters with descriptions in Google-style docstring format. The LLM generates code that calls these functions by name; the CodeAgent executes that code and passes results back to the model. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "max_steps",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " caps the number of code-generate-execute cycles before the agent stops. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "final_answer(...)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is a built-in tool the model calls when it is ready to report its result."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "smolagents: ToolCallingAgent"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For models that do not generate code well, smolagents also provides "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ToolCallingAgent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": a traditional tool-call loop where the LLM emits JSON tool-call specifications and the framework dispatches them. The API is identical to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CodeAgent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 swap the class name. Both agents accept the same tools and model."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from smolagents import ToolCallingAgent, tool, LiteLLMModel\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\n# Tools can also accept Pydantic models as structured input\nclass WeatherParams(BaseModel):\n    city: str\n    unit: str = \"celsius\"\n\n@tool\ndef get_weather(city: str, unit: str = \"celsius\") -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Get the current weather for a city.\n    Args:\n        city: The city name, e.g. 'Paris' or 'Tokyo'.\n        unit: Temperature unit, either 'celsius' or 'fahrenheit'. Default is celsius.\n    \"\"\"\n    temp = 22 if unit == \"celsius\" else 71\n    return f\"{city}: {temp} degrees {'C' if unit == 'celsius' else 'F'}\"\n\nmodel = LiteLLMModel(model_id=\"gpt-4o\")\n\n# ToolCallingAgent: LLM emits JSON tool-call specs (traditional approach)\nagent = ToolCallingAgent(\n    tools=[get_weather],\n    model=model,\n)\n\nresult = agent.run(\"What is the weather in London and Tokyo?\")\nprint(result)\n# London: 22 degrees C. Tokyo: 22 degrees C.\n\n# smolagents also supports Hugging Face Hub models directly\nfrom smolagents import HfApiModel\nhf_model = HfApiModel(model_id=\"Qwen/Qwen2.5-72B-Instruct\")\nhf_agent = ToolCallingAgent(tools=[get_weather], model=hf_model)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LiteLLMModel",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " routes to any LLM provider \u2014 OpenAI, Anthropic, Groq, Azure \u2014 using LiteLLM's unified interface. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "HfApiModel",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " calls Hugging Face Inference Endpoints directly. This makes smolagents the most flexible framework for using models that are not available through OpenAI or Anthropic. Use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ToolCallingAgent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as a drop-in for models that support function calling; use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CodeAgent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " when you want the model to reason through multi-step computation by writing code rather than declaring structured tool calls."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic AI: Defining an Agent"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic AI wraps the LLM's tool-calling loop with Pydantic validation. An "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Agent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " takes a model string, a system prompt, and optional tools. Tools are defined with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@agent.tool",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " or "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@agent.tool_plain",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "result_type",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter forces the agent's final output to be a Pydantic model, validated before being returned."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\nfrom pydantic_ai import Agent\n\n# Structured output: agent must return this shape\nclass WeatherReport(BaseModel):\n    city: str\n    temperature_celsius: float\n    condition: str  # \"sunny\", \"cloudy\", \"rainy\"\n\n# Create the agent with a model identifier and structured result type\nweather_agent = Agent(\n    \"openai:gpt-4o\",  # or \"anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\", \"groq:llama-3.1-70b-versatile\"\n    system_prompt=(\n        \"You are a weather assistant. \"\n        \"Return weather data in structured form. \"\n        \"When you don't have real data, estimate based on the city and season.\"\n    ),\n    result_type=WeatherReport,\n)\n\n# Register a tool on the agent\n@weather_agent.tool_plain\ndef get_local_temperature(city: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Look up the temperature for a city. Returns a JSON string.\"\"\"\n    # In production: call a real weather API\n    temps = {\"Paris\": 18.5, \"Tokyo\": 28.0, \"London\": 14.0, \"Cairo\": 35.0}\n    temp = temps.get(city, 20.0)\n    return f'{{\"temperature_celsius\": {temp}}}'\n\nasync def main():\n    result = await weather_agent.run(\"What is the weather in Tokyo right now?\")\n    report = result.data  # WeatherReport instance \u2014 already validated\n    print(f\"{report.city}: {report.temperature_celsius}C, {report.condition}\")\n    # Tokyo: 28.0C, sunny\n\nasyncio.run(main())"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The model string "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\"openai:gpt-4o\"",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is Pydantic AI's model routing syntax. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\"anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\"",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " routes to Anthropic; "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\"groq:llama-3.1-70b-versatile\"",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " routes to Groq. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "result_type=WeatherReport",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tells the agent that its final answer must be a valid "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "WeatherReport",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " instance. Pydantic AI handles the structured-output forcing internally \u2014 the LLM is instructed to produce JSON that matches the schema, and Pydantic validates the response before returning "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "result.data",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". If validation fails, Pydantic AI retries the LLM call with the error message."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic AI: Dependency Injection with RunContext"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic AI's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "dependency injection",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " pattern is its most distinctive feature. Define a typed dataclass for the dependencies your tools need (a database connection, an API client, a user ID). Pass "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "deps_type=MyDeps",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to the agent. Tools declare "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RunContext[MyDeps]",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as their first argument; the framework injects the dependencies when the tool is called. The LLM never sees the dependencies \u2014 they are Python-only."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\nfrom pydantic_ai import Agent, RunContext\n\n# Typed dependency container\n@dataclass\nclass AppDeps:\n    user_id: str\n    subscription_tier: str  # \"free\" | \"pro\" | \"enterprise\"\n    db_connection: object    # placeholder for a real DB client\n\nclass UserInfo(BaseModel):\n    user_id: str\n    limits: str\n    greeting: str\n\nuser_agent = Agent(\n    \"openai:gpt-4o\",\n    system_prompt=\"You are a helpful assistant that knows the user's account details.\",\n    deps_type=AppDeps,\n    result_type=UserInfo,\n)\n\n@user_agent.tool\nasync def get_user_limits(ctx: RunContext[AppDeps]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Return the rate limits for the current user's subscription tier.\"\"\"\n    limits_map = {\n        \"free\": \"10 requests/day\",\n        \"pro\": \"1000 requests/day\",\n        \"enterprise\": \"unlimited\",\n    }\n    return limits_map.get(ctx.deps.subscription_tier, \"unknown\")\n\n@user_agent.tool\nasync def get_greeting(ctx: RunContext[AppDeps]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Return a personalized greeting for the current user.\"\"\"\n    # Could query ctx.deps.db_connection here\n    return f\"Hello, user {ctx.deps.user_id}!\"\n\nasync def main():\n    deps = AppDeps(\n        user_id=\"user-42\",\n        subscription_tier=\"pro\",\n        db_connection=None,  # real DB client in production\n    )\n    result = await user_agent.run(\n        \"What are my API limits and how should I be greeted?\",\n        deps=deps,\n    )\n    print(result.data)\n    # UserInfo(user_id='user-42', limits='1000 requests/day', greeting='Hello, user user-42!')\n\nasyncio.run(main())"
          }
